Fluorescent “Off-On” and adsorption mechanisms [43] are responsible for detecting and removing the cadmium ion by LFPC nanocomposite respectively. Fluorescence quenching and its recovery are exclusively stated as an “Off-On” mechanism (Fig. 9
                        ). Quenching of blue emission of PEI-CDs is caused due to the electrostatic interaction between PEI-CDs and LaFeO3 since PEI-CDs have negative and LaFeO3 has positive surface charges as per zeta potential measurement (Fig. 10
                        ) [44,45]. On introducing cadmium ion, lanthanum orthoferrite serves as an adsorbent for the adsorbate Cd ion. Cationic lanthanum orthoferrite adsorbs the highly anionic cadmium ions [46] by releasing PEI-CDs. Thus released PEI-CDs have their own emission, leading to fluorescence recovery. On increasing cadmium ion concentration, active sites of adsorbent are occupied by the ions as a result it tends to increase the fluorescence intensity of PEI-CDs. This physical adsorption (electrostatic interaction) was confirmed by the isotherm studies, which revealed that multilayer adsorption was carried out on adsorbing cadmium ions on the adsorbent lanthanum orthoferrite.
